metadata.name: aRo #139
metadata.description:
aRo "a Representation of"

Like a ladder or a hammer, art is often a tool. The less practical and most bizarre, basically the most overcomplicated self-made tool anyone could ever imagine. But it's THE tool to explore ideas.
I created this one to investigate, to poke and nudge at a few concepts that seem to go hand-in-hand.
Firstly, Representation, as in changing something to better explain it. Metaphors, symbols, codes —the very fabric of art, religion, and society. And secondly, the aesthetics of recursion or accumulation.

While many generative art projects pick buildings and landscapes as their subject, most artworks are made of particles arranged, connected and stretched to create bigger structures, to become textures or both.

But there's a distinct texture that arises from mobs. And another, somewhat similar, that belongs to the accumulation and hoarding of not-same-objects or shapes.

I can't tell if it's a street grid, a collage, a group of shrines or actual cells, but to scratch all these potential meanings using accumulation, hoarding and mobs, is what brought the texture I was looking for.

What happens when a flower has more petals than pixels? Why do we know there's more layers to that thumbnail?
My best answer is:

--Press "s" key to save a bigger image (2400x3200 px)

metadata.name: Cube : première étude #8
metadata.description:
This work represents a study of the cube and its representation that I undertook to understand the workings of p5.js and JavaScript programming. This project, initiated this spring, allowed me to delve into various mechanics and approaches. Today, I am concluding this inaugural study on the cube and publishing it on fxhash, with the aim of sharing it and enabling others to play around with the parameters that make it up.

Thanking each individual who has contributed to this project, whether intentionally or otherwise, would be a lengthy task, and I risk forgetting someone. Therefore, a huge thanks goes out to the community here and on OpenProcessing for their ongoing exchange of advice and knowledge.

While the code remains riddled with errors, I won't be progressing further with this initial project. This will presumably allow me to avoid overworking on subsequent projects. :-)

made with p5js, p5.grain and chroma.js
on Openprocessing https://openprocessing.org/sketch/1962145

metadata.name: Plottable Clouds #47
metadata.description:
Each NFT is a recipe to a physical postcard format (A6 size) and utilizes the Redeemables feature of fxhash, allowing owners to unlock a physical plot directly from the artist @greweb. This figurative artwork is entirely generated through code, employing simple strokes and circular arcs. It may exhibit various inks, papers, and shapes.

To redeem the NFT, simply send an email directly to greweb@protonmail.com to request a physical plot from @greweb. The NFT serves as the key to obtaining a physically plottable art piece. It exports an SVG file that can be used for plotting with pens. Plotter artists have the freedom to utilize their own materials and ship the completed artwork to collectors, provided they possess the NFT at the time of the request. To obtain the .SVG file, simply drag and drop it into a folder or right-click and save.

For those interested in the technical details, this work was created using WebGL + Rust + WASM and is licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0. Additional information and the source code for this piece can be found at this link: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-clouds

metadata.name: Urban Inception Redux #59
metadata.description:
Urban Inception Redux borrows from the original Circle City project and goes bigger, 6x bigger to be exact, and adds a whole new alternate reality, more rings, and a new skew potential. 

PLEASE BE PATIENT - This project has a lot of computations and may take a minute or two to render. 

This project creates a 12 layer composition that can be exported as an SVG and plotted or used to cut a physical out of wood or acrylic using a laser. With each layer being a single contiguous element. 

More info about the project and physicals can be found at: 
https://alleditions.art/p/urban-inception-redux

Shift P - Export a PNG
Shift S - Export an SVG
Shift E - explode the layers

metadata.name: Unsquare composition #68
metadata.description:
Inspired by Jazz, Unsquare composition I experiments with the notion of non-squared rhythmic forms, where freedom and improvisation take as a premise the idea of an imperfection where we can also find harmony. 

Please do not expect perfect results.

unknowable 2022


Usage
press [s] - save .png

metadata.name: Unicorn #454
metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. But we're the only ones who can do it. We are those magical unicorns, unique, inimitable, with our own qualities and magical abilities.
These unicorns are the visualization of our inner selves that makes our dreams come true. An embodiment of all the best with a huge positive magical power.

Twitter: @unicorn_nft_art
Web: https://unicorn-nft.web.app/

by @lucky26puch, @AgataBaranova17
Made in 2022

License: CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: The muon in the hole #9
metadata.description:
Special collection for #fxhashturnsone.

Halftones, dynamic composition and contrasts.

Procedural realtime javascript / webgl.
Desktop / Chrome recommended.


Controls :
- Mouse wheel/middle/ Pinch : Zoom
- After zooming, Mouse left / Drag : Pan
- Press [r] to reset the camera.
- Press [f] to toggle the frame.
- Press [c] to fully unlock the camera, with rotation on Mouse2.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys [1] to [9] (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels for the smallest dimension. I recommend starting with [4] and going from there. What is captured is what's on screen, so you can get creative if you so desire.

NFT License

metadata.name: The Dune Sketches #16
metadata.description:
A collection of algorithmically hand-drawn landscapes. 

You can press ’s’ in live mode to save the image. 

Coded entirely in p5js.

— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —
Intended to be viewed in a Chromium based browser such as Chrome or Brave running on Version 106.0.5249.126, on a steel blue M1 iMac, on a nice mid-autumn afternoon.

metadata.name: Sunset in South Beach #188
metadata.description:
This is a collection of commemorative tokens to celebrate Art Basel 2022 in South Beach, Miami. Minting will open at 5:29 p.m. on Friday December 2nd, 2022, just as the sun is setting. 

Press 's' in Live View to save a high resolution version.

— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — —

Best viewed on Safari 16.1 on macOS (Catalina).

metadata.name: Symbolic Flux #28
metadata.description:
Generative artwork made using p5.js and WebGL

Press 1-6 to scale the output to higher resolutions.
Press 'f' to enter fullscreen.
Press 'Space' to pause animation.
Press 's' to save a high-res copy of your output.
Press 'g' to toggle grain filter.
Press 'p' to toggle post-processing filter.
Press 'b' to cycle through border sizes.
